Supervised Learning Project Solution¶

PART A¶

DOMAIN: Medical

CONTEXT: Medical research university X is undergoing a deep research on patients with certain conditions. University has an internal AI team. Due to confidentiality the patient’s details and the conditions are masked by the client by providing different datasets to the AI team for developing a AIML model which can predict the condition of the patient depending on the received test results.

DATA DESCRIPTION: The data consists of biomechanics features of the patients according to their current conditions. Each patient is represented in the data set by six biomechanics attributes derived from the shape and orientation of the condition to their body part.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: To Demonstrate the ability to fetch, process and leverage data to generate useful predictions by training Supervised Learning algorithms.

B. Share insights on correlation.

A. Features having stronger correlation with correlation value.

B. Features having weaker correlation with correlation value.

Observation:

High degree: If the coefficient value lies between ± 0.50 and ± 1, then it is said to be a strong correlation.

Moderate degree: If the value lies between ± 0.30 and ± 0.49, then it is said to be a medium correlation.

Low degree: When the value lies below ± .29, then it is said to be a small correlation.

Considering the above statements, the answers have been derived.

A. Following has strong correlation:

P_incidence has strong correlation with S_Slope (0.81), L_angle (0.72), S_Degree (0.64), P_tilt (0.63).

L_angle has strong correlation with S_Slope (0.6), S_Degree (0.53).

S_Slope has strong correlation with S_Degree (0.52).

B. Following has weaker correlation:

P_incidence -> P_radius (-0.25)

P_tilt -> P_radius (0.033)

P_tilt -> S_Slope (0.062)

L_angle -> P_radius (-0.08)

P_radius -> S_Degree (-0.026)

D. Print all the possible performance metrics for both train and test data.

In [256]:
#import libraries
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, accuracy_score
from tabulate import tabulate
In [257]:
# Add necessary functions 
def get_precision(a, b):
  return np.round(precision_score(a, b, average = 'macro'), 2)

def get_accuracy(a, b):
  return np.round(accuracy_score(a, b), 2)

def get_recall(a, b):
  return np.round(recall_score(a, b, average = 'macro'), 2)

def get_f1(a, b):
  return np.round(f1_score(a, b, average = 'macro'), 2)

def print_metrics():
    # Creating a list that we want to tabulate
    my_list = [
      ["Data Type", "Precision", "Recall", "Accuracy", "F1 Score"],
      ["Test",  get_precision(y_test, y_test_pred),
                get_recall(y_test, y_test_pred),
                get_accuracy(y_test, y_test_pred),
                get_f1(y_test, y_test_pred)],
      ["Train", get_precision(y_train, y_train_pred),
                get_recall(y_train, y_train_pred),
                get_accuracy(y_train, y_train_pred),
                get_f1(y_train, y_train_pred)],
    ]
    # Printing the tabulated list
    print(tabulate(my_list))
In [258]:
print_metrics()
print("Precision Variance = ", abs(round((get_precision(y_test, y_test_pred) - get_precision(y_train, y_train_pred)), 2)))
print("Accuracy Variance = ",  abs(round((get_accuracy(y_test, y_test_pred)  - get_accuracy(y_train, y_train_pred)), 2)))

5. Performance Improvement¶

A. Experiment with various parameters to improve performance of the base model.

In [259]:
# Build the model and train and test on training and test sets respectively using scikit-learn. 

# creating odd list of K for KNN
myList = list(range(1,20))

# subsetting just the odd ones
neighbors = list(filter(lambda x: x % 2 != 0, myList))
In [260]:
# Compare performance metrics for values from 1,3,5....19
p_distances = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
leaf = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

for k in neighbors:
  for p in p_distances:
    for l in leaf:
        knn2 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k,p = p, leaf_size = l, weights = "uniform")
        knn2.fit(X_train, y_train)
        # predict the response for test data
        y_test_pred = knn2.predict(X_test)
        # predict the response for train data
        y_train_pred = knn2.predict(X_train)
        diff = abs(round((get_accuracy(y_test, y_test_pred)  - get_accuracy(y_train, y_train_pred)), 2))
        if (get_precision(y_train, y_train_pred) != 1) and (get_precision(y_test, y_test_pred) > 0.7) and (diff <= .14):
          print("\n K = %d, p = %d, l = %d" % ( k, p,l ))
          print_metrics()
          print("Precision Variance = ", abs(round((get_precision(y_test, y_test_pred) - get_precision(y_train, y_train_pred)), 2)))
          print("Accuracy Variance = ",  abs(round((get_accuracy(y_test, y_test_pred)  - get_accuracy(y_train, y_train_pred)), 2)))

PART B¶

• DOMAIN : Banking, Marketing

• CONTEXT: A bank X is on a massive digital transformation for all its departments. Bank has a growing customer base whee majority of them are liability customers (depositors) vs borrowers (asset customers). The bank is interested in expanding the borrowers base rapidly to bring in more business via loan interests. A campaign that the bank ran in last quarter showed an average single digit conversion rate. Digital transformation being the core strength of the business strategy, marketing department wants to devise effective campaigns with better target marketing to increase the conversion ratio to double digit with same budget as per last campaign.

• PROJECT OBJECTIVE: Build a Machine Learning model to perform focused marketing by predicting the potential customers who will convert using the historical dataset.

In [283]:
def transform_categorical(data):
    categories = (data.dtypes =="object")
    cat_cols = list(categories[categories].index)
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in cat_cols:
        data[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data[col])
